 and the literate through close studies of particular cultures at specific historical moments. Rejecting the 'great-divide' theory of orality and literacy as separate and opposite to one another, the contributors posit that whatever meanings the two concepts have are products of their ever-changing relationships to one another.Through topics as diverse as Aboriginal Canadian societies, Ukrainian-Canadian narratives, and communities in ancient Greece, Medieval Europe, and twentieth-century Asia, these cross-disciplinary essays reveal the powerful ways in which cultural assumptions, such as those about truth, disclosure, performance, privacy, and ethics, can affect a society's uses of and approaches to both the written and the oral. The fresh perspectives in Orality and Literacy reinvigorate the subject, illuminating complex interrelationships rather than relying on universal generalizations about how literacy and orality function.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnalphabétisme. 0aLangage et culture. 0aLanguage and culture. 0aLiteracy. 0aOral tradition. 0aTradition orale. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aArbuckle, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlson, Keith Thor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlson, Keith Thor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChamberlin, J. Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFagan, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFagan, Kristina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGibson, Twyla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGingell, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIleto, R